16 SECTION 1.4.(a) Article 3 of Subchapter I of Chapter 7B of the General Statutes is
17 amended by adding a new section to read:
18 "§ 7B-302.1. Conflicts of interest.
19 (a) A conflict of interest shall exist when the reported abuse, neglect, or dependency
20 involves any of the following:
21 (1) An employee of the county department of social services.
22 (2) A relative of an employee of the child welfare division of the county
23 department of social services.
24 (3) A relative of an employee of the county department of social services outside
25 of the child welfare division when, in the professional judgment of the
26 director, the county department of social services has a conflict of interest.
27 (4) A foster parent supervised by the county department of social services.
28 (5) The county manager, an assistant county manager, a member of the Board of
29 County Commissioners, or a member of the county's governing board for
30 social services, as defined in G.S. 108A-1.
31 (6) A caretaker in a sole-source contract group home.
32 (7) A juvenile's parent, guardian, custodian, or caretaker who has been
33 determined to be an incompetent adult and subject to guardianship under
34 Chapter 35A of the General Statutes and is a ward, as defined in
35 G.S. 35A-1101, of that county department of social services.
36 (8) A juvenile in the custody of the department who is also a parent or caretaker.
37 (9) A juvenile who is subject to a new report of abuse or neglect arising from
38 events that occurred while in the custody of the department.
39 (10) A perceived conflict of interest that is identified through the professional
40 judgment of the director of the county department of social services.
41 (b) The director of the county department of social services that receives the report where
42 the conflict exists shall request that another county department conduct the assessment. The
43 director shall notify the Division of the conflict of interest and the county that accepted the report
44 for assessment.
45 (c) If the director makes requests of two or more other counties, and if no other county is
46 willing or able to accept the case for assessment, then the county director where the conflict exists
47 shall notify the Division. The Division shall evaluate the conflict and make the following
48 determinations:
49 (1) The Division shall evaluate the conflict and determine whether the county
50 with the conflict is able to manage the case by implementing measures to
51 sufficiently obviate the conflict.
House Bill 612-Fifth Edition Page 5

