40 SECTION 1.18.(a) Article 9A of Subchapter I of Chapter 7B of the General Statutes
41 is amended by adding a new section to read:
42 "§ 7B-909.2. Post-adoption contact agreements; orders from minors in department of social
43 services custody.
44 (a) Prior to executing a relinquishment, the parent or parents of a minor adoptee who is
45 in the custody of a county department of social services pursuant to an order entered under this
46 Subchapter and the prospective adoptive parent or parents may voluntarily participate in a
47 court-approved mediation program to reach a voluntarily mediated post-adoption contact
48 agreement. The court with jurisdiction over the proceeding involving the minor under this
49 Subchapter may make the referral to mediation when the county department notifies the court it
50 would accept a relinquishment that specifies the prospective adoptive parent or parents. A
51 biological parent who has not reached 18 years of age shall have legal capacity to enter a
Page 20 House Bill 612-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 post-adoption contact agreement and shall be as fully bound by the agreement and order as if the
2 biological parent had attained 18 years of age.
3 (b) The Administrative Office of the Courts shall develop and make available appropriate
4 standardized forms for implementation of this section.
5 (c) Jurisdiction and venue for approval of such agreement shall be before the district court
6 with jurisdiction over the proceeding involving the minor under this Subchapter.
7 (d) Other people may be invited to participate in the mediation by mutual consent of the
8 parent or parents executing a relinquishment and the prospective adoptive parent or parents.
9 However, these invitees shall not be parties to any agreement reached during that mediation and
10 shall not receive copies of any agreement.
11 (e) Mediation proceedings and information relating to those proceedings under this
12 section shall be confidential. Information or the statements of any person participating in the
13 mediation shall not be disclosed or used in any subsequent proceeding. Regardless, evidence that
14 would otherwise be admissible at trial shall not be rendered inadmissible as a result of its use in
15 a mediation proceeding. Except for the voluntary mediated agreement, there shall be no record
16 made of any mediation proceedings under this section and the mediator shall destroy all of his or
17 her notes immediately after the mediation.
18 (f) The voluntarily mediated agreement shall be reviewed by the court having jurisdiction
19 of the minor under this Subchapter within two business days of when the agreement is signed to
20 determine whether the agreement should be incorporated into a court order.
21 (g) To be approved by the court, a voluntarily mediated agreement shall be signed under
22 oath by the parties or accompanied by an affidavit made under oath that affirmatively states that
23 the agreement was entered into knowingly and voluntarily and is not the product of coercion,
24 fraud, or duress. The affidavit may be executed jointly or separately. The agreement shall contain
25 the following statements:
26 (1) This agreement is entered into pursuant to this section.
27 (2) Any breach, modification, invalidation, or termination of the agreement, or
28 any part of it, shall not affect the validity of the relinquishment or the final
29 decree of adoption.
30 (3) The parties acknowledge that either the parent or prospective adoptive parents
31 who have entered into the agreement have the right to seek enforcement as set
32 forth in G.S. 7B-909.3.
33 (4) The parties have not relied on any representations other than those contained
34 in the agreement.
35 (h) The court shall not enter an order to approve the post-adoption contact agreement
36 unless the agreement is in writing and executed prior to or as part of the relinquishment. When
37 the court approves the post-adoption contact agreement:
38 (1) The court shall enter a post-adoption contact agreement and order and instruct
39 the clerk to treat the order as an initiation of a civil action for custody.
40 (2) The court shall designate the caption of the action and the parties to the action.
41 The civil filing fee is waived unless the court orders one or more of the parties
42 to pay the filing fee for a civil action into the office of the clerk of superior
43 court.
44 (3) The post-adoption contact agreement and order shall constitute a custody
45 determination, and any motion to enforce, modify, or terminate the order shall
46 be filed in the newly created civil action and is governed by G.S. 7B-909.3.
47 The Administrative Office of the Courts may adopt rules and shall develop
48 and make available appropriate forms for establishing a civil file to implement
49 this section and G.S. 7B-909.3.
