1 (4) The record of the civil action shall be withheld from public inspection and
2 may only be examined by the parties to the civil action and their attorneys, the
3 minor adoptee, or by order of the court.
4 (i) A post-adoption contact agreement and order shall automatically terminate on the date
5 the child turns 18 years of age or is otherwise emancipated."
6 SECTION 1.18.(b) Article 9A of Subchapter I of Chapter 7B of the General Statutes
7 is amended by adding a new section to read:
8 "§ 7B-909.3. Modification, enforcement, and termination of a post-adoption contact
9 agreement and order; no right to appeal; rights of adoptive parents.
10 (a) A party to a court-approved post-adoption contact agreement and order may seek to
11 modify, enforce, or terminate the agreement by filing a motion in the civil action created pursuant
12 to G.S. 7B-909.2(h). Issues set forth in the motion shall be set for mediation unless the court
13 waives mediation for good cause. A court order for modification, enforcement, or termination of
14 the terms of the voluntarily mediated agreement shall be the sole remedies for breach of the
15 agreement.
16 (b) In a proceeding under this section, the persons who executed the post-adoption
17 contact agreement are the sole parties to the action. The court shall not allow intervention by any
18 other person or agency. The parties shall not be entitled to the appointment of counsel but may
19 retain counsel at their own expense.
20 (c) The court may modify the terms of the post-adoption contact agreement and order if
21 the court finds by a preponderance of the evidence that there has been a material and substantial
22 change in the circumstances and that the modification is in the best interests of the child. A
23 court-imposed modification of a previously approved agreement may limit, restrict, condition,
24 decrease, or terminate the sharing of information and contact between the former parent or
25 parents and the child, but in no event shall a court-imposed modification serve to expand, enlarge,
26 or increase the amount of contact between the former parent or parents and the child. The court
27 also may impose appropriate sanctions consistent with its equitable powers but not inconsistent
28 with this section, including the power to issue restraining orders.
29 (d) If the court finds that an action brought under this section was wholly insubstantial,
30 frivolous, and not advanced in good faith, the court may award attorneys' fees and costs to the
31 prevailing parties.
32 (e) A party subject to an order under this section has no right to appeal the order.
33 (f) Nothing contained in this section or G.S. 7B-909.2 shall be construed to abrogate the
34 rights of the adoptive parent or parents to make decisions on behalf of the child, except as
35 provided in the court-approved post-adoption contact agreement and order."
36 SECTION 1.18.(c) Article 1 of Chapter 50 of the General Statutes is amended by
37 adding a new section to read:
38 "§ 50-13.2B. Modification or enforcement of post-adoption contact agreement and order.
39 A former parent or adoptive parent who is party to a post-adoption contact agreement and
40 order entered pursuant to G.S. 7B-909.2 shall be governed by G.S. 7B-909.3."
