39 SECTION 1.19.(b) Article 3A of Subchapter I of Chapter 7B of the General Statutes
40 is amended by adding a new section to read:
41 "§ 7B-325. Petition for expungement.
42 (a) A person whose name has been placed on the responsible individuals list may file a
43 petition for expungement of the individual's name from the responsible individuals list if at least
44 one of the following conditions is satisfied:
45 (1) At least one year has passed since the person was placed on the responsible
46 individuals list without judicial review, though eligible for review.
47 (2) At least five years have passed since the person was placed on the responsible
48 individuals list after judicial review.
49 (3) At least eight years have passed since the person, who was criminally
50 convicted as a result of the same incident that placed the person on the
51 responsible individuals list completed their sentence, complied with all
Page 24 House Bill 612-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 post-release conditions and has not subsequently been convicted of any felony
2 or misdemeanor other than a traffic violation under a jurisdiction in this State
3 or any other United States jurisdiction. No person is eligible to petition for
4 expungement of the individual's name from the responsible individuals list
5 under this subsection if the conviction is related to sexual abuse of a child,
6 human trafficking, or a child fatality related to abuse or neglect.
7 (b) The petition for expungement shall be filed with the district court of the county in
8 which the abuse or serious neglect report arose. A copy shall be delivered in person or by certified
9 mail, return receipt requested, to the director of the county department of social services of that
10 county. The petition for expungement shall contain the name, date of birth, and address of the
11 individual seeking expungement, the name of the juvenile who was the subject of the
12 determination of abuse or serious neglect, and facts that invoke the jurisdiction of the court.
13 (c) The clerk of court shall maintain a separate docket for expungement actions. Upon
14 the filing of a petition for expungement, the clerk shall calendar the matter for hearing within 45
15 days from the date the petition is filed at a session of district court hearing juvenile matters or, if
16 there is no such session, at the next session of juvenile court. The clerk shall send notice of the
17 hearing to the petitioner and to the director of the county department of social services that
18 determined the abuse or serious neglect and identified the individual as a responsible individual.
19 Upon the request of a party, the court shall close the hearing to all persons, except officers of the
20 court, the parties, and their witnesses. The hearing shall be before a judge without a jury. The
21 burden shall be upon the petitioner and all findings of fact shall be based on a preponderance of
22 the evidence. The court may consider any evidence, including hearsay evidence as defined in
23 G.S. 8C-1, Rule 801, or testimony or evidence from any person that is not a party that the court
24 finds to be relevant, reliable, and necessary.
25 (d) At the hearing, the following rights of the parties shall be preserved:
26 (1) The right to present sworn evidence, law, or rules that bear upon the case.
27 (2) The right to represent themselves or obtain the services of an attorney at their
28 own expense.
29 (3) The right to subpoena witnesses, cross-examine witnesses of the other party,
30 and make a closing argument summarizing the party's view of the case and
31 the law. The juvenile who was the subject of the abuse or serious neglect shall
32 not be required to participate in the proceeding.
33 (e) In considering whether to grant a petition filed under this section, the court shall
34 consider all of the following:
35 (1) The nature of the abuse or serious neglect based on documentation maintained
36 by the county department of social services.
37 (2) The amount of time since the placement on the responsible individuals list.
38 (3) Any activities that would reflect upon the person's changed behavior or
39 circumstances, such as therapy, employment, or education.
40 (4) Any other circumstances relevant to whether the petition should be granted.
41 (f) The court may grant the petition if the court finds, by the preponderance of the
42 evidence, that there is little likelihood that the petitioner will be a future perpetrator of child abuse
43 or neglect.
44 (g) Within 30 days after completion of the hearing, the court shall enter an order
45 containing findings of fact and conclusions of law. The clerk shall serve a copy of the order on
46 each party or the party's attorney of record. If the court concludes that the petition should be
47 granted, the court shall order the director to expunge the individual's name from the responsible
48 individuals list.
49 (h) A party may appeal the district court's decision under G.S. 7A-27(b)(2)."
