8 SECTION 2.3. Article 2 of Chapter 108A of the General Statutes is amended by
9 adding a new Part to read:
10 "Part 4A. Guardianship Assistance.
11 "§ 108A-50.10. Kinship guardianship assistance program (KinGAP).
12 (a) Assistance. – The Division may provide for the financial support of children who
13 have exited foster care into relative guardianship that comply with 42 U.S.C. § 673. A child is
14 eligible for kinship guardianship assistance payments under this Part if the child meets the
15 requirements of subsection (b) of this section.
16 (b) Eligibility. – Until the child is 18 years of age, the child is eligible for kinship
17 guardianship assistance payments if all of the criteria are met:
18 (1) The child was removed from his or her home due to a voluntary placement
19 agreement or as a result of judicial determination to the effect that
20 continuation in the home would be contrary to the welfare of the child.
21 (2) The child was eligible for foster care maintenance payments pursuant to 42
22 U.S.C. § 672 while residing for at least six consecutive months in the home of
23 a licensed prospective relative guardian. "Relative" for the purposes of this
24 Part is a person related to the minor child by blood, marriage, adoption, or an
25 individual that has a substantial relationship with the minor child or the minor
26 child's parent prior to the child being placed in foster care.
27 (3) A determination has been made that reunification or adoption are not
28 appropriate options for the child.
29 (4) The child has attained 10 years of age and demonstrates a strong attachment
30 to the prospective relative guardian and the relative guardian has a strong
31 commitment to caring permanently for the child.
32 (5) At the time of entry into the guardianship agreement, a North Carolina county
33 child welfare agency has placement and care of the child.
34 (6) If a child is 14 years of age, the child has been consulted regarding the kinship
35 guardianship arrangement.
36 (c) Continuation of Assistance. – Individuals or youth who exited foster care under a
37 guardianship assistance agreement may continue to receive kinship guardianship assistance
38 payments after attaining 18 years of age if (i) the individual or child attained 16 years of age
39 before the kinship guardianship assistance agreement became effective, (ii) he or she chooses to
40 continue receiving guardianship services until attaining 21 years of age, and (iii) the Division
41 determines that the individual or child meets any of the following:
42 (1) Is completing secondary education or a program leading to an equivalent
43 credential.
44 (2) Is enrolled in an institution that provides postsecondary or vocational
45 education.
46 (3) Is participating in a program or activity designed to promote or remove
47 barriers to employment.
48 (4) Is employed for at least 80 hours per month.
49 (5) Is incapable of completing the educational or employment requirements of
50 subdivisions (1) through (4) of this subsection due to a medical condition or
House Bill 612-Fifth Edition Page 27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 disability that is supported by regularly updated information in the case plan
2 for the individual.
3 (d) Sibling Eligibility. – A child is eligible for kinship guardianship assistance payments
4 if (i) the child has not yet attained 10 years of age, (ii) their sibling meets the requirements of this
5 Part for kinship guardianship assistance payments, and (iii) the county child welfare agency and
6 the prospective relative guardian agree on whether the guardianship arrangement is appropriate
7 for the sibling.
8 (e) In the event of the death or incapacity of the relative guardian, the eligibility of a child
9 to receive kinship guardianship assistance payments under this Part shall not be affected by
10 reason of the replacement of the relative guardian with a successor legal guardian identified in
11 the kinship guardianship assistance agreement entered into under this Part.
12 "§ 108A-50.11. Guardianship assistance program.
13 (a) The Division may provide for the financial support of children who exit foster care
14 into legal guardianship with State funds allocated for foster care if the Division determines that
15 all of the following criteria are met:
16 (1) The child has attained 10 years of age and demonstrates a strong attachment
17 to the licensed prospective guardian and the prospective guardian has a strong
18 commitment to caring permanently for the child.
19 (2) The child is in a permanent family placement setting for at least six
20 consecutive months prior to the execution of the guardianship agreement.
21 (3) The prospective guardian is eligible to be appointed as a legal guardian
22 pursuant to G.S. 7B-600(b).
23 (4) The child is unlikely to achieve permanency through reunification or adoption.
24 (5) At the time of entry into the guardianship agreement, a North Carolina county
25 child welfare agency has placement and care of the child.
26 (6) If a child has attained 14 years of age, the child has been consulted regarding
27 the kinship guardianship arrangement.
28 (b) Individuals or youth who exited foster care under a guardianship assistance agreement
29 may continue to receive guardianship assistance payments after attaining 18 years of age if (i)
30 the individual or youth attained 16 years of age before the guardianship assistance agreement
31 became effective, (ii) he or she chooses to continue receiving guardianship services until attaining
32 21 years of age, and (iii) the Division determines that the individual or child meets any of the
33 following:
34 (1) Is completing secondary education or a program leading to an equivalent
35 credential.
36 (2) Is enrolled in an institution that provides postsecondary or vocational
37 education.
38 (3) Is participating in a program or activity designed to promote or remove
39 barriers to employment.
40 (4) Is employed for at least 80 hours per month.
41 (5) Is incapable of completing the educational or employment requirements of
42 subdivisions (1) through (4) of this subsection due to a medical condition or
43 disability that is supported by regularly updated information in the case plan
44 for the individual.
45 "§ 108A-50.12. Guardianship assistance agreement.
46 (a) In order to receive payments under this Part, the county child welfare agency shall (i)
47 negotiate and enter into a written, binding guardianship assistance agreement with the
48 prospective guardian of a child who meets the eligibility requirements of this Part and (ii) provide
49 the prospective guardian with a copy of the agreement.
50 (b) The guardianship agreement shall specify, at a minimum, all of the following:
Page 28 House Bill 612-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The amount of and manner in which each guardianship assistance payment
2 will be provided under the agreement, and the manner in which the payment
3 may be adjusted.
4 (2) The additional services and assistance that the child and guardian will be
5 eligible for under the agreement.
6 (3) The procedure by which the guardian may apply for additional services as
7 needed.
8 (4) The State will pay the total cost of nonrecurring expenses associated with
9 obtaining legal guardianship of the child to the extent the total cost does not
10 exceed two thousand dollars ($2,000).
11 (c) A guardianship agreement entered into under this section shall provide that the
12 agreement shall remain in effect without regard to the State residency of the guardian.
13 "§ 108A-50.13. Reimbursement for guardians.
14 The guardianship assistance program rates shall reimburse legal and relative guardians for
15 room and board and be set at the same rate as the foster care room and board rates in accordance
16 with rates established under G.S. 108A-49.1."
17 SECTION 2.4. The Social Services Commission shall adopt temporary rules to
18 implement the provisions of this act. The temporary rules adopted under this act shall remain in
19 effect until permanent rules are adopted that replace those temporary rules.
20 SECTION 2.5. Sections 2.1, 2.2, and 2.3 of this act are effective July 1, 2025.
