22 PART III. REVISIONS REGARDING PERMANENT NO CONTACT ORDERS AND
23 FELONY CHILD ABUSE
24 SECTION 3.1. Article 81D of Chapter 15A of the General Statutes reads as
25 rewritten:
26 "Article 81D.
27 "Permanent No Contact Order Against Convicted Sex Violent Offender.
28 "§ 15A-1340.50. Permanent no contact order prohibiting future contact by convicted sex
29 violent offender with crime victim.
30 (a) The following definitions apply in this Article:
31 (1) Permanent no contact order. – A permanent injunction that prohibits any
32 contact by a defendant with the victim of the sex violent offense for which the
33 defendant is convicted. convicted, with the victim's immediate family, or both.
34 The duration of the injunction is the lifetime of the defendant.
35 (2) Sex offense. – Any criminal offense that requires registration under Article
36 27A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes.
37 (3) Victim. – The person against whom the sex violent offense was committed.
38 (4) Violent offense. – Any of the following:
39 a. A criminal offense that requires registration under Article 27A of
40 Chapter 14 of the General Statutes.
41 b. A Class A through G felony that is not otherwise covered under
42 sub-subdivision a. of this subdivision.
43 c. An offense under subsection (b) of G.S. 14-32.4.
44 (b) When sentencing a defendant convicted of a sex violent offense, the judge, at the
45 request of the district attorney, shall determine whether to issue a permanent no contact order.
46 The judge shall order the defendant to show cause why a permanent no contact order shall not be
47 issued and shall hold a show cause hearing as part of the sentencing procedures for the defendant.
48 (c) The victim victim, the victim's immediate family, or both shall have a right to be heard
49 at the show cause hearing.
50 …
House Bill 612-Fifth Edition Page 29

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (e) At the conclusion of the show cause hearing the judge shall enter a finding for or
2 against the defendant. If the judge determines that reasonable grounds exist for the victim victim,
3 the victim's immediate family, or both to fear any future contact with the defendant, the judge
4 shall issue the permanent no contact order. The judge shall enter written findings of fact and the
5 grounds on which the permanent no contact order is issued. issued. If any member of the victim's
6 immediate family is included in the permanent no contact order, they must be specifically
7 identified. The no contact order shall be incorporated into the judgment imposing the sentence
8 on the defendant for the conviction of the sex violent offense.
9 (f) The court may grant one or more of the following forms of relief in a permanent no
10 contact order under this Article:
11 (1) Order the defendant not to threaten, visit, assault, molest, or otherwise
12 interfere with the victim.victim, the victim's immediate family, or both.
13 (2) Order the defendant not to follow the victim, the victim's immediate family,
14 or both, including at the victim's each individual's workplace.
15 (3) Order the defendant not to harass the victim.victim, the victim's immediate
16 family, or both.
17 (4) Order the defendant not to abuse or injure the victim.victim, the victim's
18 immediate family, or both.
19 (5) Order the defendant not to contact the victim victim, the victim's immediate
20 family, or both by telephone, written communication, or electronic means.
21 (6) Order the defendant to refrain from entering or remaining present at the
22 victim's residence, school, place of employment, school, or place of
23 employment of the victim, the victim's immediate family, or both, or other
24 specified places at times when the victim victim, the victim's immediate
25 family, or both are present.
26 (7) Order other relief deemed necessary and appropriate by the court.
27 …
28 (h) At any time after the issuance of the order, the State, at the request of the victim, or
29 the defendant may make a motion to rescind or modify the permanent no contact order. If the
30 court determines that reasonable grounds for the victim victim, the victim's immediate family, or
31 both to fear any future contact with the defendant no longer exist, the court may rescind or modify
32 the permanent no contact order.
33 …."
34 SECTION 3.2. G.S. 14-318.4 reads as rewritten:
35 "§ 14-318.4. Child abuse a felony.
36 (a) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
37 years of age who intentionally inflicts any serious physical injury upon or to the child or who
38 intentionally commits an assault upon the child which results in any serious physical injury to
39 the child is guilty of a Class D felony, except as otherwise provided in subsection (a3) of this
40 section.
41 (a1) Any A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than
42 16 years of age, or any other person providing care to or supervision of the child, age who
43 commits, permits, or encourages any act of prostitution with or by the child is guilty of child
44 abuse and shall be punished as a Class D felon.
45 (a2) Any A parent or legal guardian of any other person providing care to or supervision
46 of a child less than 16 years of age who commits or allows the commission of any sexual act
47 upon the child is guilty of a Class D felony.
48 (a3) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
49 years of age who intentionally inflicts any serious bodily injury to the child or who intentionally
50 commits an assault upon the child which results in any serious bodily injury to the child, or which
Page 30 House Bill 612-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 results in permanent or protracted loss or impairment of any mental or emotional function of the
2 child, is guilty of a Class B2 felony.
3 (a4) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
4 years of age whose willful act or grossly negligent omission in the care of the child shows a
5 reckless disregard for human life is guilty of a Class E felony if the act or omission results in
6 serious bodily injury to the child.
7 (a5) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
8 years of age whose willful act or grossly negligent omission in the care of the child shows a
9 reckless disregard for human life is guilty of a Class G felony if the act or omission results in
10 serious physical injury to the child.
11 (a6) For purposes of this section, a "grossly negligent omission" in providing care to or
12 supervision of a child includes the failure to report a child as missing to law enforcement as
13 provided in G.S. 14-318.5(b).
14 (a7) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
15 years of age who, for the purpose of causing fear, emotional injury, or deriving sexual
16 gratification, intentionally and routinely (i) inflicts physical injury on that child and (ii) deprives
17 that child of necessary food, clothing, shelter, or proper physical care is guilty of a Class B2
18 felony.
19 …
20 (1k) Serious bodily injury. – Bodily injury that creates a substantial risk of death
21 or that causes serious permanent disfigurement, coma, a permanent or
22 protracted condition that causes extreme pain, or permanent or protracted loss
23 or impairment of the function of any bodily member or organ, or that results
24 in prolonged hospitalization.
25 (2) Serious physical injury. – Physical injury that causes great pain and suffering.
26 The term includes serious mental injury."
27 SECTION 3.3. Prosecutions for offenses committed before the effective date of this
28 act are not abated or affected by this act, and the statutes that would be applicable but for this act
29 remain applicable to those prosecutions.
30 SECTION 3.4. Sections 3.1 and 3.2 of this act become effective December 1, 2025,
31 and apply to offenses committed on or after that date.
